The algorithm for recovering the AGN light curves relies heavily on the \emph{SEXtractor}\cite{SEXtractor} software \cite{SEXtractorGuide} and the reference star catalogues of \emph{PanSTARRS\cite{PanSTARRS}} and \emph{2MASS\cite{2MASS}}. 

\subsection[The use of SEXtractor]{The use of SEXtractor\footnote{The information in this section relies heavily on \cite{SEXtractorGuide} and the website \url{sextractor.readthedocs.io}\cite{SEXtractorDOCS}}}
The SEXtracotor software determines a global background map and uses it to isolate pixels, or groupings of pixels, not belonging to the background (for more information see the \emph{SEXtractor User's Guide\cite{SEXtractorGuide}}). The SEXtractor call specified the parameters that should be returned:
\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=1.\linewidth]{Figure/SEXtractor_call.png}
\caption{The SEXtractor call in the light curve code.}
\label{fig:SEXtractor}
\end{figure}
\noindent The \emph{"XMODEL\_WORLD", "YMODEL\_WORLD, "XMODEL\_IMAGE"} and \emph{"YMODEL\_IMAGE"} gives the location of the objects found in SEXtractor in Celestial Coordinates and pixel coordinates respectively. The \emph{"FLUX\_RADIUS(1)"} and \emph{"FLUX\_APER"} designates that the sampling method is aperture, and that the entirety of the flux in the aperture is to be returned (the SEXtractor standard is 0.5). The \emph{"DETECT\_THRESH"} and \emph{"DETECT\_MINAREA"} commands designates the required expectation for an object to be returned in \emph{$\sigma$ above background noise} and \emph{minimum size of the pixel groupings}. \emph{"PHOT\_FLUXFRAC"} should be considered legacy code, and specifies the fraction of light inside the \emph{half-light radius} of the object, should such be queried. \emph{"PHOT\_APERTURES"} is the diameter of the aperture chosen (in pixels). Aperture photometry in general risks running the danger that the number of pixels inside the aperture changes dependent of small changes in the observed coordinates. This problem is resolved in SEXtractor by dividing all pixels into groups of $5\times5$ sub-pixels.\\
\\
A search algorithm was created to determine the closest SEXtractor object to the expected location of the astronomical object of interest. This search algorithm was created to exclude the outer 15 pixels of the images as allowed locations for the reference star psf center points, due to the early realisation that it was an oft occurring phenomenon that parts of the stellar psf would otherwise fall outside the image, thus creating unaccounted scatter by reducing the effective size of the stars. It was decided to allow an astrometrical inaccuracy of $\pm 10\ pixels$, this has not caused any undue confusion between astronomical objects in the image frames. The search algorithm is shown in \emph{figure \ref{fig:search_algorithm}}.
\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=1.\linewidth]{Figure/search_algorithm.png}
\caption{The search algorithm to identify the relevant astronomical objects in the image frames.}
\label{fig:search_algorithm}
\end{figure}


\subsection{The Standard Stars}

The AGN flux was found through the use of simultaneously sampled standard stars, in the same image, by the use of a re-arranged version of \emph{equation \ref{eq:app_mag}} and the known standard star magnitudes obtained from \emph{PanSTARRS} and \emph{2MASS} combined with the known zero-magnitude flux rates (\emph{table \ref{tab:zero_mag_tab}}). The standard star role in the creation of AGN light curves from observational data is, crucial (J. Palmer \& A.C. Davenhall 2001\cite{CCD:COOK}). Where applicable multiple standard stars has been utilised in this project in an attempt to confirm the obtained fluxes, to have alternatives for overexposed stars, such as the NGC3783 plate HD 101274 in the griz bands (\emph{figure \ref{fig:saturation_ross2}}) and to counter the possibility of a star being out of the frame due to the image orientation (like the NGC3783 plate Tycho-2 7740-529-1). In this project a pletora of standard stars has been utilised, however as the \emph{PANSTARRS survey} does not extend below a declination angle of $-30^{\circ}$ it has been necessary to do a magnitude calibration on all reference stars in the griz bands below this limit. This has been done through the utilisation of the same code as the AGN flux determination and utilising \emph{equation \ref{eq:app_mag}}, with $F_{1}/F_{2}$ being the relative observed fluxes. The Standard Stars and their magnitude calibrations, whether they be from \emph{2MASS}, \emph{PANSTARRS} or done in the course of this project can be seen in \emph{tables \ref{tab:stand_star_JHK} \& \ref{tab:stand_star_griz}}.
