\subsection{The error on the AGN light curves}
The \emph{signal-to-noise ratio} (see \emph{section \ref{error}}) was determined based on the sampling of background sky variation (the sky-background contribution to the shot-noise in the pre-background subtracted JHK band images (for further discussion on the nature of shot noise see \emph{Hughes \& Hase 2010\cite{Hughes2010}})) in three different locations, located around the AGN, that were pre-determined to have no expectation of viewable astronomical objects. For this purpose the previously \emph{accurate astrometry method} was utilised, due to the unimportance of the exact sky location in an uninhabited area. The use of three different locations was chosen to minimize the potential effect of cosmic ray hits, and any effects originating from differences arising across the image plate. The different sky-background variations obtained was combined and analysed as one and the error obtained from the different objects (AGN and standard stars) becomes (\emph{Hughes \& Hase 2010\cite{Hughes2010}})
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
F_{AGN} = k\frac{signal_{AGN}}{signal_{standard star}}\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \Rightarrow \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \\
\alpha_{F_{AGN}}=F_{AGN}\sqrt{\bigg(\frac{\alpha_{signal_{AGN}}}{signal_{AGN}}\bigg)^{2}+\bigg(\frac{\alpha_{signal_{standard star}}}{signal_{standard star}}\bigg)^{2}},
\end{split}
\label{eq:divide_error_eq}
\end{equation}
with $\alpha$ being the \emph{signal-to-noise ratio} and $F$ the flux. The \emph{signal-to-noise ratio} were further analysed to understand the contribution from either the \emph{signal}, the \emph{sky-background} or the \emph{RON}. The error propagated through rearrangement of \emph{equation \ref{eq:app_mag}} is
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
F_{*} = F_{ref}10^{\frac{m_{ref}-m_{*}}{2.5}} \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \Rightarrow \\
\alpha_{F_{*}} = \frac{ln(10)\alpha_{m_{*}}}{2.5}F_{ref}10^{\frac{m_{ref}-m_{*}}{2.5}},
\end{split}
\label{eq:raised_to_10_error}
\end{equation}
with $F_{ref}$ and $m_{ref}$ being the reference flux and magnitude respectively that is being used for calibration, in this project the vega zero-magnitude for the JHK bands, and the AB zero-magnitude values for the griz bands. $F_{*}$ and $m_{*}$ is the standard star flux and magnitudes, while $\alpha_{m_{*}}$ is the error in the standard star magnitude, either as determined in this project for the griz bands at declination below $-30^{\circ}$, or the relevant PanSTARRS (griz) or 2MASS (JHK) values. As
\begin{equation}
\alpha_{Signal_{AGN}} = \frac{Signal_{AGN}}{SNR_{AGN}}
\label{eq:error_signal_SNR}
\end{equation}
and the propagated error of multiplied variables are
\begin{equation}
Z = A \times B \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \alpha_{Z} = Z\sqrt{\bigg(\frac{\alpha_{A}}{A}\bigg)^{2} + \bigg(\frac{\alpha_{B}}{B}\bigg)^{2}},
\label{eq:error_minus}
\end{equation}
thus reducing the total error to
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
F_{AGN} = \frac{signal_{AGN}}{signal_{*}}F_{ref}10^{\frac{m_{ref}-m_{*}}{2.5}} \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \  \Rightarrow \\
\alpha_{F_{AGN}} = \frac{signal_{AGN}}{signal_{*}}F_{ref}10^{\frac{m_{ref}-m_{*}}{2.5}}\times \sqrt{\bigg(\frac{1}{SNR_{AGN}^{2}} + \frac{1}{SNR_{*}^{2}}\bigg) + \frac{ln(10)\alpha_{m_{*}}}{2.5}}.
\end{split}
\label{eq:tot_error}
\end{equation}
This is naturally baring the assumption that no error is found on the zero-magnitude flux itself, an assumption not entirely accurate (\emph{table \ref{tab:zero_mag_tab}}), but compared to the \emph{signal-to-noise ratio}, and the uncertainty in the standard star magnitude, this systematic, and minor, inaccuracy in the zero-magnitude flux is negligible. \\
\\
